This major commit refactors the entire user guide and its examples to create a single, cohesive, and well-structured learning resource within the `docs` directory.

Key changes:
- A new directory structure is established under `water_system_sdk/docs/guide/source/`, where each chapter now has its own subdirectory (`ch03`, `ch04`, etc.).
- All Python example scripts and data files (`.json`, `.yml`) associated with the 32-chapter guide have been moved into their corresponding new chapter subdirectories.
- All markdown files for the guide (Chapters 3-32) have been updated to point to the new, organized file locations.
- The `README.md` and `index.md` files are consistent with this new structure.

This effort unifies the documentation and its code examples, creating a self-contained and easy-to-navigate learning center for all users of the SDK.

pull_request.body:
Bumps [mini_magick](https://github.com/minimagick/minimagick) from 4.13.2 to 5.3.0.
Release notes

Sourced from mini_magick's releases.

v5.3.0

  • Actually require Ruby 2.5+ in the gemspec.
  • Fix Ruby 2.5 compatibility when using MiniMagick.restricted_env configuration.
  • Drop benchmark dependency.
  • Fix keyword argument forwarding when trying to call MiniMagick.compare(errors: false)

v5.2.0

  • Added MiniMagick.restricted_env configuration for stopping IM command from inheriting environment variables from the parent process.
  • Fixed "ambiguous * has been interpreted as an argument prefix" warning

v5.1.2

  • Add benchmark gem to runtime dependencies

v5.1.1

  • Add logger gem to dependencies for Ruby 3.4+.

v5.1.0

  • New cli_env configuration was added for setting extra environment variables for every CLI command:

    MiniMagick.configure do |config|
  config.cli_env = { "MAGICK_MEMORY_LIMIT" => "128MiB" }
end

  • New graphicsmagick configuration was added for telling MiniMagick to use GraphicsMagick instead of MiniMagick:

    MiniMagick.configure do |config|
  config.graphicsmagick = true # prepend all commands with "gm"
end

    Previously, the recommended approach was setting MiniMagick.cli_prefix = "gm", but that doesn't work when ImageMagick 7 is installed, as in that case MiniMagick will try to prepend magick on top of gm.

v5.0.1

  • MiniMagick::Image#write doesn't delete the internal tempfile anymore, which restores use cases like:

    image = MiniMagick::Image.open("...")
image.resize("500x500")
image.write("foo.jpg")
image.blur
image.write("bar.png")

  • Prevented MiniMagick::Image#to_ary being called by ruby in certain cases, such as [image].flatten(1).

issue.title: Feature Request: Save Special Journal Dates to Google Calendar for Yearly Reminders
issue.body:
Description:
Currently, PocketLIFE allows users to write daily entries (thoughts, birthdays, achievements, etc.).
I propose integrating Google Calendar API so that special entries can be saved as events in Google Calendar.

Proposed Flow:

User writes a daily entry.

If the entry contains important tags (like birthday, offer, celebration, achievement) or if user manually marks it as special,

The app will create a Google Calendar event on that date.

The next year, the user receives a reminder notification (through Google Calendar).

Benefits:

Keeps users emotionally connected to their past memories.

Adds a practical reminder system to the journal.

Makes the app more personalized and useful over time.

Tech Suggestions:

Integrate with Google Calendar API.

Extend user settings to allow linking Google account.

Add a toggle/button in journal entry like "Save this as Calendar Event".

Future Scope:

Option to auto-scan entries for words like "birthday", "anniversary", "offer", and suggest adding to calendar.

Add ability to set custom reminders (e.g., 1 day before, 1 week before).
